{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Andreas* (Chapter 1), one notable instance where a storm (\"**storm**\") is directly named as the subject of the action occurs during the heathens' mistreatment of Andrew, as they drag him through the streets:**\n\n> Storm upp aras æfter ceasterhofum, cirm unlytel hæþnes heriges.[^1]\n\nThis line (approximately line 1235 in standard editions) depicts the storm suddenly arising amid the city's courts, accompanying the heathens' loud tumult (\"cirm\"). The Old English word \"**storm**\" (nom. sg., \"storm\") serves as the grammatical subject, effectively \"naming\" the phenomenon in a concise, personified manner typical of Old English poetry.[^1]: /works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-34b202\n\nOther storm references appear elsewhere (e.g., \"**storme** bedrifene\" at the giant-built pillars, \"storm-driven\" ~line 1494; \"**stormas** restan,\" \"storms to rest\" ~line 1575; or \"**storm** ne mæg,\" \"no storm can\" ~line 501), but this is the clearest case where \"**storm**\" names the entity rising dramatically.[^2]: /works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/transliteration/#p-992aeb\n\n[^2]: Multiple passages confirmed via `search_corpus(\"storm\")`; OE from `read_chapter(..., variant=\"original\")`. The translation renders it \"A storm rose up through the city-courts\" in the relevant spot.",
